@singletrackrunning Fourmidable 50k is a Team USA Selection race in 2023! 

In 2019, I ran this race as my 50k debut, as it was also a team selection race that year.

I flew into Reno from Santa Barbara, since it was a cheaper option, on Thursday thinking it would give me all of Friday to be there before the race. However, old man winter had different plans, and Mike and I stayed in Reno an extra night waiting out a storm. 

After waiting most of Friday for the roads to open, we started embarking on our way, only to meet two more highway closures, turning what would usually be a 2-hour drive into a 10+ hour adventure. (It would have been more time efficient to have driven from Santa Barbara). 😂

We were ill-prepared for the winter conditions and underestimated how long we would be in the car, so I ate an entire bag of tortilla chips to get some carbs in for the big race and napped when I could.

After grabbing some food as we approached Auburn, we eventually arrived at our Airbnb at 11 pm.

Overall I was pretty calm as I went to bed. And when I woke up I gave no thought to the previous day and instead showed up to the line with the intention of racing my heart out.

It had oddly snowed the day before, providing unusually high frost cold water crossings. But even despite this, the front women's pack never let up. After taking the lead around 10 miles, I never took my foot off the pedal as the next women were hot on my tail.

After a grueling 4-ish hours of racing, which included multiple waist high snow melt crossings, I would eventually finish the race in first place and with the second fastest time ever for the course. 

The takeaways from this race were rarely can pre-race obstacles deter good fitness if you go with the flow, and a bag of tortilla chips can do wonders if you are in a pinch.👌🥔

I have had a lot of people doubt me in my life. People who don’t believe in me, call me crazy, ask me why I commit myself to something when I won’t hit my goals, and more.

When I’ve had rough days or seasons, these same types of people have told me to quit or that my “best days are behind me”.

While hard in the moment, these remarks have had a direct effect on how I pursue my passions, especially running. The most prominent being that I learned at a young age that the mind is powerful when it comes to blocking out negativity. But like anything else, requires practice and attentiveness.

While at first the challenge of blocking negativity can be tough, it’s something that can translate extremely well to training and competition. 👌😉

Inch by inch, step by step.

My career to this point has been pretty gradual. Each year building upon the rest, as I delicately play the balance game between work, running, and my relationships outside of these spheres. 

It requires a lot of hard work and attentiveness to being aware of who I am and where I want to be. My North Star are the goals I set for myself, some tangible and many that seem impossible.

At times people have told me “how lucky I am” in which case I tell them I have made my own luck. I’ve made it by saying yes to opportunity and challenges, I’ve made it with tears dripping down my face, and I’ve made it by getting back up when people would understand if I decided to stay on the ground.

I am a darn hard worker who isn’t afraid to pull their sleeves up when the going gets tough. I have had a job since I legally was allowed to, I worked through college while being a student-athlete and paid of my student loans instead of spending my money on ‘fun’ stuff, I put in my time when I want to be better at something, and listen to learn.

I am not an overnight sensational nor will I ever be. But I am damn proud of how hard I work to make gains in the areas of my life I treasure most. Chipping away isn’t always exciting, but it’s what works for me and I’m enjoying every step of the way.

I’m a blue collar runner, but above that I am Dani. ♥️

My #1 training tip: EAT, EAT, EAT.

I am about to enter the final phase of my Boston training cycle, and while I have a strong focus on intervals and recovery, right alongside those is fueling with @springenergy for nearly every run (not just baddies).

While it can be hard to eat when it’s cold outside, fueling is critical in winter because my body needs calories to stay warm. And staying warm keeps my immune system robust and my muscles supple.

I strongly believe that my commitment to fueling even on the coldest days contributed to a big PR in the half-marathon this past weekend. 💪🍎🍌🍐

I am now officially a road marathoner! I chose the @bostonmarathon for my debut because I wanted to challenge myself, and boy did I ever. 

I was able to work with a group of women who had a similar time goal as me starting from mile 2, and it was nice to have each other's support as the headwind and rain picked up. We hit the half at 1:17 and stayed together until Heartbreak Hill. Although we started to break apart afterwards, I was still on pace for a sub-OTQ time of 2:36 with 6k to go. However, shortly thereafter I began to bonk ( I am thinking due to some fueling timing) which added enough time to finish in 2:38:23 and 33rd place.

Does it hurt? Absolutely. While the bonk pain wore off after some rest, my heart is still a bit disappointed. But am I proud? Hell yeah! I trained through one of the hardest seasons of life and weather I've ever endured. What little free time I had was mostly spent shoveling this winter, and I felt that slowly wearing on me. Despite that, I still put in good work and stepped up to the starting line today knowing that, no matter what the weather would be, I had a good chance. And for that, I want to pat myself on the back.

As a first marathon experience, I don't know how anything could top the fans, volunteers, and atmosphere of Boston. This place was magical in every way possible. What made it even more special though was having my coach, parents, fiancé, and a few friends there along the way. It's truly something I will never forget.

I want to thank everyone who helped keep my body together through this crazy winter. I couldn't have done it without you! And to all my family and friends who cheered me on today and in the days leading up to it, I love you all!

Also congrats to all the badass ladies in that field today. It was an honor to be there, and I hope to return some day on the future! Your performances were awe inspiring. 

As for my next shot at an OTQ, that's TBD. For the remainder of the year a majority of my races will include a bit more dirt and vert.😉

#oneteam

As I look back on last weeks’ @bostonmarathon , it was initially hard for me to accept how close I was to my goal. To some, it may have seemed like just a 90-second miss, but for me, it was about holding on for another 2 miles.

I've spent a good amount of time reflecting on the experience and thinking about what I could have done differently. However, after a few days, I started to see the beauty in the challenge that is Boston. Instead of feeling disappointed, I began to think, "damn, Dani, you were so close! Hell yeah!"

I chose the challenge. I chose to dive into the deep end, and I chose the hard road. Whether or not I captured my goal, I'm proud to be the kind of person who chooses difficult things.

In my opinion, I made a lot of good decisions for race tactics, but I know there are still large improvements to be made in my fueling. Despite not having the paper trail to prove it, I know that I can run a much faster time in the marathon. And I'll do it. It just wasn’t on last Monday.

One additional takeaway I wasn't expecting from this experience was that it was the first training block where I wished I had more time to train, not just in the lead-up to the race but in my day-to-day life. Even though I take a lot of pride in working in tech and competing at a top level, I've been craving a change. After all, we only have one life, and it's finite. So maybe it's time for some big life changes.

Thanks again to all the messages I received on the lead up and post race, I felt all the love and I’m so excited to get back after it.

“Just because you can doesn't mean you should.”

These wise words from my coach @terryhowell5  have been a guiding light in my athletic journey over the past few years. It's easy to fall into the trap of constantly pushing ourselves to our limits, but it's crucial to balance our drive with self-respect and self-care.

Recently, I faced a tough decision - whether to race last weekend or prioritize recovery. Trusting my gut and my coach, I chose to rest and focus on preparing for the upcoming summer season. Although it wasn't an easy decision, I knew it was the right one for me, and it allowed me to recharge both physically and mentally.

After Boston, I found myself craving another chance, but sometimes, missing our goals is a necessary part of the journey. It can be tough, and we may feel the need to prove ourselves to others, but we must remember that the work was done regardless, and the only validation we need is our own.

Embracing the discomfort of missing a goal and respecting the pendulum swing is crucial for our growth as athletes and individuals. Consistently performing at our best is challenging, but picking ourselves back up after a setback is equally challenging. 

This weekend was a helpful reminder that taking care of myself and respecting the ‘misses’ is essential to achieve my more loftier goals in the long run.

Endless winter brings afternoon rainstorms, painting the skies with rainbows 🌈🤩.

I’m gradually recovering my legs after the double this past weekend. Surprisingly, they feel quite good, but I always trust my coach’s guidance. This time, my coach has advised me to take an extra day of easy miles before resuming adaptive training. Until then, I’ll embrace the rain and continue my afternoon strolls.

Last week I had an amazing time in Olympic Valley that gave me a large boost of dopamine. 

I celebrated my birthday with friends from all over the world and had a blast at the @takethebridge event.

Aside from these moments, I had a profound moment of gratitude and felt connected to something greater. Last year, during the WSER weekend, I watched @ruthcrofty and @emilyhawgood supporting and running with each other on the live stream while I was in Chamonix preparing for MBM. It deeply resonated with my vision of what teamwork should be like in our sport.

And now, I'm part of THAT team.🥹♥️

Observing our team's preparations for the race was incredibly impressive. As I watched them meticulously plan and execute their strategies, earning each of themselves a top ten, I was in awe and inspired.  And I know whenever I decide to enter this arena, I'll have some of the best mentors to seek advice from.

As a team, we all made valuable contributions, and I had the wonderful opportunity to support my TERREX teammate @vom.gluecker in his first WSER race. Janosch was going through a difficult phase, but he remained one of the kindest individuals I've ever met. We worked together to keep him in the hunt for top ten, focusing on intention and form. His determination and strength during that section was incredibly inspiring. In the end, he triumphed and finished in the men’s top ten, and tears filled my eyes as he crossed the finish line with his wife @miriamsamira 🥹

Meanwhile, my dear friend @rod.farvard had the race of his life and narrowly missed the top ten, finishing 11th in the men’s race in one of the most competitive years. In the last ten miles, Rod overtook four competitors and closed a 12-minute gap. I was ecstatic when I saw him running into the stadium. Not long ago, he was recovering from a broken leg, silently working hard. I already knew what an exceptional athlete Rod is, but seeing him come back even stronger brought tears to my eyes.

This years WSER will forever hold a special place in my heart.

Thank you WSER ♥️

During my time in Europe, I had the privilege of spending numerous quality moments with my @adidasterrex teammates,  in training ,racing, and all the moments in between.

They say you become the average of the people you surround yourself with, and if that's true, I am immensely grateful to be surrounded by such exceptional athletes and wonderful human beings to learn from.

Throughout our conversations, one perspective stood out the most: 'success,' however each individual defines it, often comes when we're having a lot of fun.

And fun can take various forms - whether it's the exhilaration of speed work, the joy of spending long days in the mountains, cherishing time with friends, or supporting them in their pursuits.

I am genuinely thankful to my teammates for being a never-ending source of inspiration. And, I eagerly look forward to reuniting with many of them in August!

✨Trying is Cool ✨

Last week, I spoke to some high schoolers about my running career and was asked what advice I'd give my younger self. I shared insights about patience, believing in the process, and more. However, a few days later during a run, a crucial realization struck me—I'd tell not only my younger self but also other young athletes that 'trying is cool.'

It's entirely acceptable to exert effort and follow your passions. While some may critique or ridicule your ambitious pursuits, always remember that you're remarkable just as you are.

The path of endeavor isn't always a parade of rainbows and butterflies; at times, you might become overly engrossed, encounter challenging lessons, and grapple to maintain equilibrium. There will be failures and moments when you don't quite reach your goals. Yet, this is all perfectly okay.

Throughout it all, you'll come to understand that giving your utmost is an intrinsic part of who you are. As you forge connections with more kindred spirits, this unwavering commitment will become infectious. Moreover, you'll find that some of the most valuable life lessons are learned through your persistent efforts and willingness to try, again and again. 

And hey,  while your path was not always linear, your trying will pay off. Despite people telling you to move on from your dreams and that you need to move on to ‘real life’, you will become a professional athlete and it’s all because you kept trying and believed in yourself . But even if it never happened, you are a much cooler person for trying at all.♥️

What I thought were period cramps, turned into some weird mix of food poisoning and a stomach bug- not sure what it was completely but it wasn’t good.

For nearly three days nothing stayed in my system and I couldn’t run. 

I rested and my team did everything they could to help me feel better. 

The day before the race food was finally staying, and we were all crossing our fingers it may be just enough. 

My race plan changed drastically, and racing to win shifted to other goals. 

The warm up for the race already felt like a marathon, but I was still hopeful that the body just needed to get going.

From the gun it quickly became clear that my tank had been too empty for too long. I tried to mitigate and eat and drink as much as could, but the amount of effort I was putting out still only gave me fragments of output. 

I drifted back in the field within the first mile and every mile after I drifted further; Trying desperately to salvage something. 

At champex-lac I felt like I had already completed the entire race and some, but I wanted to try a few more mental tricks before ultimately making the tough but very necessary call to cut it at Trient.

I was sad, angry, mad, and disappointed. But before I knew it I had a big smile on my face cheering on my friends and teammates as they had some incredible performances. Esp @tonimccann with one helluva win 👑❤️🥹

I know I’ll be sad for a bit longer, but also know that I’ll be getting on a start line before I know it. Yes the ‘Superbowl’ for my distance has passed, but there are still many great races remaining and I can’t wait to compete in one or a few of them.

So coming to a race start soon, Dani Moreno with a full belly of fuel. 😘

While I’m disappointed I didn’t secure a ‘big win’ this year, I take pride in my progress. As I reflect on where I could have improved, I balance that disappointment with recognizing how far I’ve come and how my hard work is translating into improvement.

To all fellow runners pursuing their personal goals, keep at it. Success for most of us won’t happen overnight; it’s built through years of consistency, intention, and unwavering dedication. Personally, I know that when I achieve my goal, it will be the result of years of attentiveness and the unwavering love and support of those closest to me.

My work ethic, determination, and consistency will always guide me, even when motivation fluctuates. I also hope that when I finally secure that ‘big one,’ it will mark the beginning of another chapter in my journey, not the end.

A few more weeks of the season await, and instead of continuing to push, I plan to conclude the season while hopefully feeling fresh—a sensation I haven’t experienced in years. I recently heard a wonderful quote about pet companionship: 'For us, it may be just a chapter, but for them, it's their whole life.' 🐾🥹

River has brought us immense joy for four unforgettable years. When we first rescued him, we were seeking an athletic, 50-60lb dog, one that could 'scare away bears and mountain lions,' as I often joked. 😂

After hours of searching on Petfinder, we discovered a litter of puppies saved from a kill shelter. It didn't take long for us to realize that River, whom we initially found online, was the one. They speculated he might have some Mastiff and Labrador in him, indicating he'd be a big boy. We hadn't planned on a large dog, but we felt he had chosen us during the adoption process.

Initially, we were taken aback at the thought of having a really big dog, but we quickly adjusted our lives to welcome our soon-to-be larger furry friend. We even had fun speculating with our friends about how big he'd be based on his 'HUGE' paws. (Looking back, those paws were quite small 😅, but sometimes you make your own signs.)

To our surprise, our vet informed us after six months that River would end up around 40lbs. We laughed, thinking there must be a mistake – he's a Mastador, after all. 🤣😂 She replied, 'Well, look at him; he's on the smaller side.' 😂

Before we knew it, River, at his smaller size, became the perfect, fun-loving companion we could have hoped for. 🐶

It was a great reminder that you can make all the decisions and plans you want, but life has a way of giving you what you need, not necessarily what you expect. And that's perfectly great. 🌟

Happy Four Years, River boy! ❤️❤️❤️❤️

📸 @cody.mathison

✨A magical 10 days in Europe with my love 🥰

Originally, I had planned to end my season with Les Templiers, but when I found out I needed to qualify for OCC before the end of the year, my best option was Kodiak 53km.

However, Mike had already bought his ticket to crew me in my first longer race, and it wasn't refundable. So we thought, 'Well, I guess we can go to Europe without a race' 🤷🏻‍♀️😂 – something I had never done in my life. We traded in what would have been another work trip for a full vacation 🤩.

After Kodiak, while my body felt fine and like I could keep training and racing, my mind and emotions needed a refill from the hard work I put in over the year. So I committed to just over two weeks of no running, and it ended up being filled with amazing experiences with my love at home and abroad.

In Europe we walked along the coast, ate great food, explored historic sites, and listened to podcasts about all the areas we were visiting. With bases in Antibes and Rapallo, we were able to see a lot of the Riviera. Despite all these experiences, my favorite part was simply spending one-on-one time with my best friend, with no obligations besides relaxation.

We finished the trip with a few days in Berlin to visit a friend.

Over the years, I've come to really appreciate and love taking time off. We train our bodies all year to recover between efforts, so while our bodies may be okay after a few days off there's the benefit of extra physical rest, coupled with the mental rest. And that mental & emotional rest is what is most important for performance and consistency over the years in my opinion.

Now, I'm excited to dive into the next phase of recovery – no training, just fun adventuring for now, and then we'll begin again with the hard workouts and pushing the needle to get ready for 2024.

So yes big fan of off seasons and encourage it for everyone, as hard as it may be at times. It’s a game changer ❤️

When I say 'attainable,' I recognize that nothing is ever a given. There's always something that can happen. However, I find that I thrive with goals that seem somewhat out of reach from where I am currently in my life. The 'dream big or go home' mantra is a strong oversimplification, but it is a style of goal-setting I thoroughly enjoy.

So, when I had a recent few weeks where I was really struggling to find why I felt so unsettled, I journaled, talked to friends, my partner, and coach. Ultimately, I discovered that for where I am right now and the races I have laid before me, I just needed to make my dreams a little bigger.
